items.synopsis: Back on home soil for the first time since the World Cup, Australia take on world number 63 Iran as they get their Olympic qualification underway.

title.children: Matildas face Iran in first Olympic qualifier in Perth

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: And it's Ellie Carpenter who opens the scoring!! A great fizzing run from Cortnee Vine down the right sees the ball pinged backwards towards the penalty spot, right into the feet of Charlotte Grant. Instead of putting her own foot through it, she takes a moment and squares for Carpenter, who'd ghosted into the box from the right side. She takes a controlling touch and slams it through the red legs of Iran's defenders and beneath the outstretched arm of goalkeeper Zahra Khajavi. 1-0!
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: 18' GOAL AUSTRALIA

children.content: And it's Ellie Carpenter who opens the scoring!!
A great fizzing run from Cortnee Vine down the right sees the ball pinged backwards towards the penalty spot, right into the feet of Charlotte Grant.
Instead of putting her own foot through it, she takes a moment and squares for Carpenter, who'd ghosted into the box from the right side.
She takes a controlling touch and slams it through the red legs of Iran's defenders and beneath the outstretched arm of goalkeeper Zahra Khajavi.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Aaaaand your friendly neighbourhood live-blogger was right! Most of the big-name Matildas we saw during the World Cup like Caitlin Foord, Mackenzie Arnold, Steph Catley, Hayley Raso, Katrina Gorry, Alanna Kennedy - as well as Sam Kerr - are starting on the bench tonight against Iran. Instead, we've got starts for players we didn't get to see much of earlier this year: Nevin, Wheeler, Chidiac, Micah, Yallop, and a much-deserved start for the young Amy Sayer, one of the only new inclusions into the squad this window. Who catches your eye of these new starters, team? Who do we reckon will do something special tonight?
